<CONTENT id="_800667_1"><TITLE value="Topic 1.2: The Turing test"/><TITLECOLOR value="#000000"/><DESCRIPTION
   value=""/><BODY><TEXT>&lt;div data-layout-row="c12995f0-0f67-41fe-a2e6-064308311aef"&gt;&lt;div data-layout-column="97dcb11e-5362-48ca-9552-2d6f4a44f363" data-layout-column-width="12"&gt;&lt;div data-bbid="bbml-editor-id_0e0d3726-6c10-4e13-92f1-4a0b52ad075e"&gt;&lt;h4&gt;Topic 1.2: The Turing test&lt;/h4&gt;&lt;h5&gt;1950 Alan Turing&lt;/h5&gt;&lt;p&gt;In 1950, the legendary computer scientist and mathematician&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style="color: #000000"&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Alan Turing&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style="color: #000000"&gt;,&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;proposed a test that was designed as a thought experiment. The purpose of this test was to see if a computer could learn to mimic human behavior. The question to be answered was:&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p style="text-align: center;"&gt;&lt;span style="color: #1c8845"&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: 1.5rem;"&gt;Can machines think?&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;He defined intelligent behaviour as the ability to achieve human-level intelligence during a &lt;span style="color: #000000"&gt;&lt;strong&gt;conversation&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;. This performance should be sufficient to trick an interrogator into thinking that the answers are coming from a human.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;h6&gt;Watch this video to learn more about Turing's experiment and the main AI fields of discipline:&lt;/h6&gt;&lt;p style="text-align: center;"&gt;&lt;a href="https://mediasite.centennialcollege.ca/Mediasite/Play/51657db5d9af417cb3df6c8ae75715261d" data-bbtype="video" data-bbfile="{&amp;quot;src&amp;quot;:&amp;quot;https://mediasite.centennialcollege.ca/Mediasite/Play/51657db5d9af417cb3df6c8ae75715261d&amp;quot;,&amp;quot;alt&amp;quot;:&amp;quot;https://mediasite.centennialcollege.ca/Mediasite/Play/51657db5d9af417cb3df6c8ae75715261d&amp;quot;}"&gt;https://mediasite.centennialcollege.ca/Mediasite/Play/51657db5d9af417cb3df6c8ae75715261d&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;h6&gt;The experiment:&lt;/h6&gt;&lt;ul&gt;&lt;li&gt;The test requires a program to have a conversation (via typed messages) with an interrogator for five minutes.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;The interrogator then has to guess if the conversation is with a computer or a real person.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;The interrogator will not be able to see or hear the respondent on the other side. The figure below illustrates the test environment:&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ul&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="@X@EmbeddedFile.requestUrlStub@X@bbcswebdav/xid-1692493_1" data-bbtype="attachment" data-bbfile="{&amp;quot;alternativeText&amp;quot;:&amp;quot;Turning test environment&amp;quot;,&amp;quot;linkName&amp;quot;:&amp;quot;M1_Turning_test.jpg&amp;quot;,&amp;quot;mimeType&amp;quot;:&amp;quot;image/jpeg&amp;quot;,&amp;quot;render&amp;quot;:&amp;quot;inline&amp;quot;}"&gt;M1_Turning_test.jpg&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;To enable this setup, a human will be interacting with two entities called &lt;span style="color: #000000"&gt;&lt;strong&gt;respondents&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style="color: #000000"&gt;,&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;one of whom will be human and the other will be a machine.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;In order to &lt;span style="color: #000000"&gt;&lt;strong&gt;pass &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;the Turing test, the computer would need to possess the following capabilities:&lt;/p&gt;&lt;ol&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style="color: #000000"&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Natural language processing (NLP)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;: to enable it to communicate successfully in English.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style="color: #000000"&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Knowledge representation:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt; To store what it knows and hears.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style="color: #000000"&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Automated reasoning&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;: to use the stored information to answer questions and to draw new conclusions.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style="color: #000000"&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Machine learning&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;: to adapt to new circumstances and to detect and extrapolate patterns.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ol&gt;&lt;p&gt;The program passes the test if it &lt;em&gt;fools&lt;/em&gt; the interrogator &lt;span style="color: #000000"&gt;&lt;strong&gt;30%&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt; of the time.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;h6&gt;Examples:&lt;/h6&gt;&lt;p&gt;Turing conjectured that by year 2000, a computer with a storage of a billion units could pass the test.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Here we are today and we cannot agree if a program has passed the test. Nevertheless, the following are examples of Chat-bots today that have fooled humans:&lt;/p&gt;&lt;ol&gt;&lt;li&gt;ELIZA (click the following link for more information &lt;a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ELIZA"&gt;ELIZA&lt;/a&gt;)&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;MGONZ&amp;nbsp;(click the link for more info&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href="https://computing.dcu.ie/~humphrys/turing.test.html"&gt;MGONZ&lt;/a&gt;)&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;NATACHA&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;CYBERLOVER (attracted attention and Law enforcement)&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;Eugene Goostman&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ol&gt;&lt;h5&gt;Turing Total test (Second test)&lt;/h5&gt;&lt;p&gt;Other researchers have proposed a test that requires&lt;span style="color: #000000"&gt;&lt;strong&gt; interaction&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt; with objects&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;This test includes a video signal so that the interrogator can test the subject’s perceptual abilities, as well as the opportunity for the interrogator to pass physical objects “through the hatch.”&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;In order to&lt;span style="color: #000000"&gt;&lt;strong&gt; pass &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;the Turing Total Test, the computer would need to possess the following capabilities:&lt;/p&gt;&lt;ol&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style="color: #000000"&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Computer vision:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt; to perceive objects&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style="color: #000000"&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Robotics:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt; to manipulate objects and move about&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ol&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;h5&gt;References&lt;/h5&gt;&lt;ol&gt;&lt;li&gt;Artificial intelligence a modern approach&amp;nbsp;by Stuart J. Russell and Peter Norvig, Chapter 1&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ol&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</TEXT><TYPE
